title: SFH visits Yau Tsim Mong District (with photos)
content_text:
p>
          The Secretary for Food and Health, Dr Ko Wing-man, visited Yau Tsim 
          Mong District this afternoon (March 14) to familiarise himself with 
          the elderly health-care services and public market facilities in the 
          district, and to exchange views with District Councillors on local 
          affairs under his purview. Dr Ko first visited the Salvation Army's Mong Kok Integrated Service 
          for Senior Citizens Hoi Yu Day Care Centre for Senior Citizens to see 
          services provided by the centre to the elderly in the district, which

services provided by the centre to the elderly in the district, which 
          include personal care, treatment and rehabilitation services. Dr Ko 
          was glad to learn that the centre has participated in the Pilot 
          Project on Outreach Primary Dental Care Services for the Elderly in 
          Residential Care Homes and Day Care Centres. Under the Pilot Project, 
          free outreach primary dental care and oral health care services are 
          being provided to the elderly in the centre. The Government launched the Pilot Project in collaboration with 
          non-government organisations for a period of three years starting from

non-government organisations for a period of three years starting from 
          April 2011. Free on-site primary dental care services, including 
          dental check-up, scaling, polishing and any other necessary pain 
          relief and emergency dental treatments are provided to the elderly 
          concerned. Oral care training programmes are given to caregivers of 
          the residential care homes and day care centres concerned. Oral health 
          education activities such as seminars and talks are also held for the 
          elderly concerned, their family members and caregivers. The Pilot

elderly concerned, their family members and caregivers. The Pilot 
          Project will cover attendance of more than 100 000, benefiting some 80 
          000 elderly in residential care homes and day care centres. Dr Ko then proceeded to the Yau Ma Tei Market and chatted with stall 
          operators and local residents to hear their views on the further 
          improvement of public market services. Dr Ko concluded his visit at a 
          meeting with Yau Tsim Mong District Councillors, with whom he 
          exchanged views and suggestions on how to improve services in health,

exchanged views and suggestions on how to improve services in health, food safety and environmental hygiene. Ends/Thursday, March 14, 2013
Issued at HKT 19:27
